    Kurkihar bronze pedestal dedication, Rājyapāla year 28

    Metadata

    Current Version:  draft, 2022-08-12Z

    Editors:   Vincent Tournier.

    DHARMA Identifier: Kurkihar-Rajyapala-year28

    Hands: Standard Pāla-period Siddhamātr̥kā. Example of repha integrated into the akṣara below its headline are found in line 3 mārga and ācāryo, and in line 4 kīrttir.

    Apparatus

    1 -caturvedimaṅgalākhyo PLG GB ◇ caturvedī maṅgalākhyo AB-S • AB-S’s reading comprises a silent, unnecessary emendation. On caturvedimaṅgala, an equivalent of agrahāra used in the Tamil-speaking South as a suffix to villages granted tax-free to Brahmins, see Sircar 1965: 377; IEG, s.v.

    Translation

    I.
    There is a village named Narasiṁhacaturvedimaṅgala, which adorns the illustrious Kāñcī, and is esteemed by the excellent ones, the noble ones,

    II.
    [and is a] pleasing resting place for twice-borns who master the Vedas and Vedāṅgas. There, in a pure lineage of brahmins [vipra], he who is endowed with virtues, took birth.

    III.
    He became the disciple of the venerable Vairocanasiṁha—[himself] an ocean of virtues—and [came to be] called Prajñāsiṁha, esteemed among the virtuous ones.

    IV.
    He, relying on the correct Dharma, with devotion ordered to be made this image of the Sugata, made of pure brass, which is resplendent as it is rubbed (by devotees).

    V.
    By the merit, may the world, together with [his] teacher and preceptor, joined by [his] mother and father, reach the state of sugatas!

    VI.
    While King (kṣitibhr̥t) Śrī-Rājyapāla was ruling the earth, during [his] 28th year, on the 8th day of the waxing (sita) [fortnight of the month] of Vaiśākha (i.e., on the Buddha’s birthday), [this] most excellent memorial was made.

    Bibliography

    First edited by A. Banerji-Sastri (19401940: page 246, № 52), whose reading was reproduced by S. Huntington (1984: pages 213–214). An improved edition had by that time already been offered by P.L. Gupta (1965: page 155, № 164). The third edition, by G. Bhattacharya (2000: page 95), is inferior to Gupta’s, as it comprises several silent emendations and printing or typing errors. Although Banerji-Sastri’s summary is presented as such by Huntington and, more curiously, by Bhattacharya, no translation has been published so far. Edited and translated here by Vincent Tournier (09.2020), based on the photograph from the Huntington archive.
